INSERT INTO `ef_posts` VALUES('111', '1', '2015-04-03 17:36:52', '2015-04-03 17:36:52', 'If you’ve wandered down the beverage aisle of a grocery store lately, you’ve probably noticed that there is now a stunning array of choices. This is due to a major shift in consumer preference. Sugary soda has gotten bad press for its contributions to obesity, diabetes, and heart disease, and diet soda has been controversially linked to cancer and weight gain. This has spurred consumers to seek healthier choices, and soda companies are feeling the impact: soda consumption in the US has steadily declined over the past decade, and Diet Coke sales are down 15 percent since 2013.\r\n\r\nEuromonitor predicts that over the next five years, global sales of soda will only increase 8 percent, while sales of bottled water will jump 32.6 percent, and other nonalcoholic beverages will increase by 20 percent. As consumers cast about for their new beverage of choice, brands are racing to get their attention. Coca Cola and Pepsi have expanded into water, vitamin drinks, energy drinks, coconut water, and sparkling juices, but smaller companies have an opportunity to compete against them in these newly popular categories. The secret to success? Packaging.\r\n\r\nWith so many options on the shelf, brands have a hard time getting noticed, and an even harder time getting considered or purchased. One eye-tracking study we conducted found that shoppers noticed 133 soft drinks (spent 0.3 seconds or more looking at them) but only evaluated five of them (spent more than 0.5 seconds looking at them), picked up two of them, and purchased two of them. With long odds like these, having attractive packaging is crucial.\r\n\r\nAccording to “Packaging Matters,” a 2013 study by MeadWestvaco, packaging drives 36 percent of purchase decisions, “moreso than TV ads, online reviews and recommendations from friends.”\r\n\r\nA recent white paper by Affinova shows that in the energy drink market, advertising is no match for package design. Red Bull, Monster, and Rockstar are consistently the top three brands. Coca Cola has two energy drink brands on offer, NOS and Full Throttle, but both brands have a tiny and declining market share: NOS fell from 3.6 to 3.3 percent from 2010 to 2013, and Full Throttle fell from 2.2 percent to not even registering as a major competitor. This despite massive amounts of advertising dollars—NOS increased ad spending by 187 percent from 2010 to 2012, and Full Throttle outspent Monster and Rockstar combined.\r\n\r\nWhen evaluating packaging personality, consumers give these two products the lowest scores of any energy drink brands. They are not considered cool, fun, or energizing. The only personality trait that both rated positive on was “extreme.” Coca Cola would do better to focus its resources on can design than to continue wasting money on advertising.\r\n\r\nIn a recent package design study for a large carbonated soft drink company, we found that on shelf, shoppers were significantly more drawn to the a new package design (90 percent of shoppers looked for more than 3.0 seconds) versus the current one (76 percent looked for 1.7 seconds). The new package definitely drew more attention, but did this lead to purchase? Yes it did. In fact, the new design was purchased at a rate almost double the existing design during that study.\r\n\r\nAccording to an article in Design Management Journal, packaging redesign can yield as much as 50 times the ROI as advertising. “Investment in package design is far more lasting than for advertising, sales promotion, or direct marketing,” author Rob Wallace asserts. “Quite simply, packaging is a far more pervasive and permanent part of the brand communications platform than any other marketing tool.”\r\n\r\nIf you’re experiencing sluggish sales or having trouble breaking into your market, increasing the ad budget may not be the answer. A packaging redesign could be more effective and more affordable.\r\n\r\nThe place to start is an eye tracking study. Eye tracking will tell you if consumers are noticing and considering your product, and it will show which aspects of competitors’ design attract shoppers’ attention. Contact us to learn more about how eye tracking will help you create a successful packaging design.', 'Standing Out from the Crowd: The Beverage Aisle and the Importance of Package Design', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'beverage-aisle-package-design', '', '', '2015-04-03 17:36:52', '2015-04-03 17:36:52', '', '0', 'http://ef.zendentest.com/?p=111', '0', 'post', '', '0');
