INSERT INTO `ef_posts` VALUES('113', '1', '2015-04-03 17:41:30', '2015-04-03 17:41:30', 'Most people like to think that they make logical buying decisions based on price, trust in a brand, recommendations from a friend, etc. These can all be factors, of course, but consumer research shows that shoppers’ decisions start from a much deeper place—the subconscious level.\r\n\r\nMost information actually never reaches the conscious mind. Estimates vary, but maybe 10 percent of information ever penetrates the conscious level. A consumer can’t buy something that he or she doesn’t notice, so products must make the move from the subconscious mind to the conscious mind in order to even be considered. It’s only at the consideration point that a product may be converted to a sale.\r\n\r\nThe first step to getting noticed is eye fixation, something we know a little about. The human eye switches between movement and stillness. Our research has found that the movements, which individuals are largely unaware of, last about 20–40 milliseconds (ms), and the still periods last about 100–400 ms. Once fixated, the eye takes in visual information about a 2-degree angle around the fixation location, and everything else is seen in peripheral vision, which is quite coarse.\r\n\r\nTransitioning from the fuzzy mass of information in a shopper’s peripheral vision to become an object of fixation is a challenge for brands. The best way to do this varies by product, but some suggestions include placing the product near eye level (ideally from 30 degrees below eye level to about 10 degrees above eye level), adding standout images, using bright colors and faces, reducing text, and incorporating movement.\r\n\r\nEven a conscious fixation on something does not always mean it’s written into memory or noticed. In an eye-tracking study we conducted in a music store, one subject fixated on items of interest (products and signs) 245 different times in 5 minutes. Another fixated 1,569 different times in 15 minutes. When asked afterwards to recall whether they’d seen specific signs, the subjects rarely remembered those they had looked at—they had seen too many things.\r\n\r\nIn order to reduce the information overload of fixating on so many items, our  subconscious processing narrows our “consideration set”—i.e., the products we notice. Cereal, for example, may be stacked from floor to top shelf down an entire row, but consumers who aren’t buying for kids may completely ignore the bottom shelves. Salad dressings are arranged by brand, each with a distinctly shaped bottle, so consumers will zero in on a familiar-looking group of bottles and ignore everything else.\r\n\r\nThe consideration set can be used to attract attention to other products, especially for private-label items. A private-label product that looks similar to a name-brand product will attract more attention and consideration from consumers than if its packaging were distinct. This is why someone looking for Cheerios is likely to notice the similar yellow box of Toasted Oats, and then he or she may do a price comparison and go for the cheaper option.\r\n\r\nIt’s at this point, when shoppers are considering an item, that they start to use past experiences, feelings about the product or brand, and in-store influences like sales or price to determine if the item is something they want to purchase.  \r\n\r\nWhether you’re launching a new product or trying to increase sales of your current product, understanding how consumers’ brains process visual information is critical to your success. Moving a product from the subconscious mind to fixation to consideration can be challenging, but doing so effectively can be the key to success.', 'The Buying Process: Subconcious Triggers to Conscious Action', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-buying-process-subconcious-triggers-to-conscious-action', '', '', '2015-04-03 17:41:30', '2015-04-03 17:41:30', '', '0', 'http://ef.zendentest.com/?p=113', '0', 'post', '', '0');
