INSERT INTO `ef_posts` VALUES('115', '1', '2015-04-03 17:43:17', '2015-04-03 17:43:17', 'If you work in the grocery industry, you know all too well that  the retail food sector faces a great paradox in consumer demand: If you want people to continue to buy food from your store, you have to waste food—a lot of food.\r\n\r\nThe USDA estimates that 10 percent of the total available food supply goes to waste at the retail level, resulting in a loss of 43 billion pounds of food and $16 billion in 2010. The problem here  is not that supermarkets are being careless. They know exactly what they’re doing: keeping the customers happy.\r\n\r\nAs shopper insight experts and shoppers ourselves, we know that when customers walk into a grocery store, they expect to see perfection; no bruised produce, no depleted deli cases, and no dented cans. Everything should be pleasing to the eye, plentiful, and nothing should be flawed. In order to meet these high aesthetic expectations, supermarkets and the people who run them end up throwing away vast amounts of perfectly edible food.\r\n\r\nThe produce aisle is an excellent example. Shoppers don’t want to see a bin with even a few soft, bruised apples sitting on the bottom; they want to see a towering stack of crunchy, shiny apples. Grocery managers routinely order more apples than they expect to sell and throw them out as soon as they show any signs of softening or bruising Consumer value on the look of their fresh produce contributes to 13 billion pounds of losses in fruits and vegetables annually.\r\n\r\nThe deli is another area of a grocery store that suffers a lot of food loss due to overstocking. Nielsen has identified “assembling” meals instead of preparing meals as a major consumer trend. While people are making fewer trips to the grocery store overall (56 average trips in 2012, compared with 72 in 2001), convenience food sales were up, in some case by double digits, just between 2013 and 2014. But keeping the deli case and nearby displays of freshly packaged meals stocked comes at a cost.\r\n\r\nA paper by the Natural Resources Defense Council (NRDC) explains that while some of the loss can be offset by using meat and produce that are nearing their expiration date, keeping the ready-made food fully stocked through the end of the night results in large amounts of food being tossed out after closing. One grocer estimated that half of his rotisserie chickens were thrown away every night.\r\n\r\nFood loss is not limited to fresh foods, though. Damaged packaging—such as dented cans—makes food unsellable. While the food inside may still be safe to eat, consumers won’t buy these items for fear of rot or botulism, and stores wisely remove them from the shelf.\r\n\r\nPackaged foods are also wasted because of “sell by” dates. However, we know that these dates are simply meant tell you how long to display items on shelves, and that they have little to do with food safety and are not mandated by federal law. But consumers confuse “sell by” dates with “use by” dates, thinking that food is expired long before it really is. Many stores even get rid of food a few days before the “sell by” date to appease these squeamish buyers. The NRDC reports that supermarkets lose an estimated $2,300 per day on out-of-date foods.\r\n\r\nFor those in the grocery industry, these types of food waste are just part of a daily reality. No one would argue there isn’t value in consumer opinion, and a radical shift in consumer demand seems unlikely. However, there are steps that can be taken to reduce loss.\r\n\r\nWould customers buy those less-than-perfect items if they got a great deal? Some stores have begun offering discounts on about-to-expire produce and packaged items. The Berkeley Bowl, a local market in Berkeley, California, offers a shelf of $0.99 items that are close to expiration. The market reports selling $1,500 per day from this shelf.\r\n\r\nComposting food waste could be an effective way to go “green” and save some green along the way. New Seasons Markets, which operates 12 stores in the Pacific Northwest, started composting in 2006. The grocery chain has diverted over 2,410 tons from landfills and saved nearly $27,000 in waste expenses by doing so.\r\n\r\nGiving back to those in need—which may also help boost employee morale—can be achieved by donating still-edible items to a local food bank. SUPERVALU, Inc., which owns brands including Albertsons and Stop ’n Save, has donated the equivalent of 48 million meals since 2010 and saved $2.6 million in doing so.\r\n\r\nCheck out the EPA’s Food Recovery Challenge for more ideas about reducing waste, as well as resources to help implement new strategies. With proper food safety education, the way customers shop may change over time, but for now, considering the impact of changing how the grocery industry reduces waste will also impact the businesses’ bottom line.', 'Consumer Demand Is Costing You: Why Retailers Have to Waste Food', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'consumer-demand-is-costing-you-why-retailers-have-to-waste-food', '', '', '2015-04-03 17:53:23', '2015-04-03 17:53:23', '', '0', 'http://ef.zendentest.com/?p=115', '0', 'post', '', '3');
INSERT INTO `ef_posts` VALUES('116', '1', '2015-04-03 17:43:17', '2015-04-03 17:43:17', 'If you work in the grocery industry, you know all too well that  the retail food sector faces a great paradox in consumer demand: If you want people to continue to buy food from your store, you have to waste food—a lot of food.\r\n\r\nThe USDA estimates that 10 percent of the total available food supply goes to waste at the retail level, resulting in a loss of 43 billion pounds of food and $16 billion in 2010. The problem here  is not that supermarkets are being careless. They know exactly what they’re doing: keeping the customers happy.\r\n\r\nAs shopper insight experts and shoppers ourselves, we know that when customers walk into a grocery store, they expect to see perfection; no bruised produce, no depleted deli cases, and no dented cans. Everything should be pleasing to the eye, plentiful, and nothing should be flawed. In order to meet these high aesthetic expectations, supermarkets and the people who run them end up throwing away vast amounts of perfectly edible food.\r\n\r\nThe produce aisle is an excellent example. Shoppers don’t want to see a bin with even a few soft, bruised apples sitting on the bottom; they want to see a towering stack of crunchy, shiny apples. Grocery managers routinely order more apples than they expect to sell and throw them out as soon as they show any signs of softening or bruising Consumer value on the look of their fresh produce contributes to 13 billion pounds of losses in fruits and vegetables annually.\r\n\r\nThe deli is another area of a grocery store that suffers a lot of food loss due to overstocking. Nielsen has identified “assembling” meals instead of preparing meals as a major consumer trend. While people are making fewer trips to the grocery store overall (56 average trips in 2012, compared with 72 in 2001), convenience food sales were up, in some case by double digits, just between 2013 and 2014. But keeping the deli case and nearby 