me green along the way. New Seasons Markets, which operates 12 stores in the Pacific Northwest, started composting in 2006. The grocery chain has diverted over 2,410 tons from landfills and saved nearly $27,000 in waste expenses by doing so.\r\n\r\nGiving back to those in need—which may also help boost employee morale—can be achieved by donating still-edible items to a local food bank. SUPERVALU, Inc., which owns brands including Albertsons and Stop ’n Save, has donated the equivalent of 48 million meals since 2010 and saved $2.6 million in doing so.\r\n\r\nCheck out the EPA’s Food Recovery Challenge for more ideas about reducing waste, as well as resources to help implement new strategies. With proper food safety education, the way customers shop may change over time, but for now, considering the impact of changing how the grocery industry reduces waste will also impact the businesses’ bottom line.\r\n\r\n\r\nTAGS: Grocery, Retail, Consumer Behavior, Shopper Research', 'Consumer Demand Is Costing You: Why Retailers Have to Waste Food', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '115-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-04-03 17:43:17', '2015-04-03 17:43:17', '', '115', 'http://ef.zendentest.com/115-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
